<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:38.497 --> 00:40.956
- My name is Brandon Brink,
and I've been a bladesmith now

00:41.000 --> 00:42.499
for about three years.

00:42.543 --> 00:44.376
<i> I'm actually</i>
<i> a big baby at heart.</i>

00:44.420 --> 00:47.963
I'm a "sensitive" Viking,
I guess you could say.

00:48.007 --> 00:50.340
- My name is Pete Winkler.
I'm 63 years old.

00:50.384 --> 00:52.176
<i> I've been bladesmithing</i>
<i> and forging knives</i>

00:52.219 --> 00:54.011
<i> for about four years.</i>

00:54.055 --> 00:56.722
I was born to be a knife-maker,
but I'm a grandpa first.

00:56.766 --> 00:58.474
<i> We have 24 grandchildren,</i>

00:58.517 --> 01:03.771
and I look forward
to just passing the craft on.

01:03.814 --> 01:06.690
<i> - My name is April Franklin.</i>
<i> I'm 43.</i>

01:06.734 --> 01:10.152
I made my first knife
in 1999.

01:10.196 --> 01:11.653
<i> I'm a woman</i>
<i> in a man's field.</i>

01:11.697 --> 01:13.280
I ain't here to get
a pedicure.

01:13.324 --> 01:15.532
<i> I mean, I want to make</i>
<i> the best knife I can</i>

01:15.576 --> 01:17.951
and hopefully walk out of here
with $10,000.

01:17.995 --> 01:20.120
[laughs]

01:20.164 --> 01:22.915
<i> - My name's Jo Smith.</i>
<i> I'm from Jinx, Oklahoma.</i>

01:22.958 --> 01:25.250
I got my start as a bladesmith
because of my father.

01:25.294 --> 01:26.960
He's been a taxidermist
and hunting guide

01:27.004 --> 01:30.172
for all of my life,
and using a knife every day.

01:30.216 --> 01:32.174
<i> My dad's my hero.</i>

01:32.218 --> 01:33.592
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:33.636 --> 01:37.096
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the junkyard.

01:37.139 --> 01:38.430
You're here
for three rounds

01:38.474 --> 01:39.765
of edged weapon-making
competition

01:39.809 --> 01:41.266
designed to test
every aspect

01:41.310 --> 01:43.644
of your blade-making
capabilities.

01:43.687 --> 01:45.479
At the end of each round,
you will present your work

01:45.523 --> 01:48.357
to our panel
of expert judges.

01:48.400 --> 01:52.069
World-renowned
master bladesmith, Jason Knight.

01:52.113 --> 01:55.114
Internationally known historic
weapons recreations specialist

01:55.157 --> 01:57.116
and swordsmith,
David Baker.

01:57.159 --> 02:00.077
And last, globally recognized
Kali martial artist

02:00.121 --> 02:02.204
and edged weapons specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

02:02.248 --> 02:03.914
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:03.958 --> 02:05.457
If you haven't guessed by now,
the reason

02:05.501 --> 02:07.376
you're at this junkyard
is because in round one,

02:07.419 --> 02:08.877
you'll be harvesting
the steel

02:08.921 --> 02:10.462
that you need to make
a signature blade

02:10.506 --> 02:14.216
in your signature style
from the junk outside this door.

02:14.260 --> 02:16.009
And in case that
wasn't hard enough,

02:16.053 --> 02:18.095
you'll also
be using these.

02:18.139 --> 02:20.681
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:20.724 --> 02:22.474
- Yeah!

02:22.518 --> 02:26.353
We go to this junkyard,
and I get to use a coal forge.

02:26.397 --> 02:29.648
Wow.
Totally in my comfort zone.

02:29.692 --> 02:32.276
- Today you'll be using
a coal forge.

02:32.319 --> 02:35.070
First round of competition,
we're going old-school.

02:35.114 --> 02:38.949
You will have to forge
and hammer your blades by hand.

02:38.993 --> 02:40.909
There are no power hammers
or gas forges

02:40.953 --> 02:42.661
here in the junkyard.

02:42.705 --> 02:44.371
Keep in mind that
in the second round,

02:44.415 --> 02:45.789
you'll be attaching handles
to your blades

02:45.833 --> 02:47.624
to turn them
into fully functional weapons

02:47.668 --> 02:49.668
that will then be tested
for strength and durability

02:49.712 --> 02:51.420
in a coconut chop,

02:51.463 --> 02:54.256
and for sharpness
in a sandbag slice.

02:54.300 --> 02:56.341
Due to the difficulty
of this round,

02:56.385 --> 02:59.052
you will have four hours
to work on your blades,

02:59.096 --> 03:01.805
with no design period.

03:01.849 --> 03:04.683
The blades themselves must fall
within the following parameters.

03:04.727 --> 03:06.435
<i> The length of the blade,</i>
<i> not including the tang,</i>

03:06.478 --> 03:09.813
<i> must be</i>
<i> between 10 and 12 inches.</i>

03:09.857 --> 03:11.440
<i> The overall length</i>
<i> of your weapon</i>

03:11.483 --> 03:14.484
<i> must not exceed</i>
<i> 22 inches.</i>

03:14.528 --> 03:18.697
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your time starts...now.

03:18.741 --> 03:21.700
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

03:21.744 --> 03:24.703
- Find a piece of junk.
Oh, this is my heaven.

03:24.747 --> 03:27.497
This is my Disneyland.
I love using reclaimed steels.

03:27.541 --> 03:29.124
<i> So I'm looking around,</i>
<i> and I see</i>

03:29.168 --> 03:30.709
<i> all these other</i>
<i> different types of steels.</i>

03:30.753 --> 03:33.629
<i> I see spring steels.</i>
<i> I see flat leaf spring.</i>

03:33.672 --> 03:35.047
My jaw hit the floor.

03:35.090 --> 03:38.175
I was in absolute
steel junk heaven.

03:38.219 --> 03:40.260
<i> What I have laying around</i>
<i> in my home forge</i>

03:40.304 --> 03:43.096
is pretty much
all junkyard materials.

03:43.140 --> 03:44.848
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:44.892 --> 03:46.767
<i> - Using junkyard steel,</i>

03:46.810 --> 03:49.519
you can't really guarantee
what you're grabbing.

03:49.563 --> 03:53.523
My game plan is to find
a piece of steel that's flat,

03:53.567 --> 03:55.484
that's about the right thickness
that I need,

03:55.527 --> 03:58.278
<i>so I can cut down on the amount</i>
<i> of work I have to do.</i>

03:58.322 --> 04:00.656
- Jo, right away,
comes away with a leaf spring.

04:00.699 --> 04:02.574
- That's wisdom.

04:02.618 --> 04:04.409
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:04.453 --> 04:06.370
- I'm doing leftovers.
- Yeah.

04:06.413 --> 04:07.746
Let's do it.
- Here we go.

04:07.790 --> 04:09.831
- Pete and I both have
the same idea.

04:09.875 --> 04:12.584
We go for the leaf springs.
We know it's good steel.

04:16.590 --> 04:19.341
- That spring steel's
a very forgiving metal.

04:19.385 --> 04:20.968
It's a wonderful metal
to work with.

04:21.011 --> 04:23.136
It's what a lot of people
start with,

04:23.180 --> 04:24.346
because it's
so forgiving.

04:24.390 --> 04:26.431
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:26.475 --> 04:30.602
<i> - I glance over and I see</i>
<i> this huge piece of tool steel.</i>

04:30.646 --> 04:32.854
This is what I'm gonna use.

04:32.898 --> 04:34.189
- With the exception
of Brandon,

04:34.233 --> 04:35.857
everybody picked out
a leaf spring.

04:35.901 --> 04:38.360
- Problem Brandon's
gonna have is

04:38.404 --> 04:40.988
he's gonna have to work
that down, right?

04:41.031 --> 04:43.031
They don't have to work it down.
They're just gonna profile

04:43.075 --> 04:45.492
and pull it out.

04:45.536 --> 04:47.869
- Whoo!
Hot damn, son.

04:47.913 --> 04:48.954
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:48.998 --> 04:50.372
- I see a lot of grinding,

04:50.416 --> 04:53.458
and I don't see
a lot of fires going.

04:53.502 --> 04:55.460
What they should've done
was lit their fires first.

04:55.504 --> 04:57.838
- Get that coal burning.
- Yeah.

04:57.881 --> 05:02.342
There's an art to maintaining
and manipulating the coal forge.

05:02.386 --> 05:04.845
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:04.888 --> 05:06.972
- Come on, now.

05:07.016 --> 05:10.392
Yeah, baby.
Give me some fire.

05:10.436 --> 05:13.145
- All right, so Brandon's
got his forge going.

05:13.188 --> 05:15.981
- My game plan right now
is I really don't have one.

05:16.025 --> 05:18.066
No blade design.

05:18.110 --> 05:20.235
I'm just going with the steel,
see what it wants to give me.

05:20.279 --> 05:25.365
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:25.409 --> 05:29.119
- Jo, very fast
lighting his forge.

05:29.163 --> 05:31.246
- Game plan this round is just
to put something together

05:31.290 --> 05:32.831
that should perform.

05:32.875 --> 05:35.167
Gonna be making
a competition knife,

05:35.210 --> 05:37.753
something that's got
a good feel to it,

05:37.796 --> 05:40.547
and designed to chop.
Nothing else.

05:40.591 --> 05:43.133
It's gonna just chop,
chop, chop.

05:43.177 --> 05:46.470
The only concern I've got
is working with a coal forge.

05:46.513 --> 05:49.181
Instead of being able to heat up
the whole piece in a gas forge,

05:49.224 --> 05:52.142
in a coal forge you're just
doing little sections of it.

05:52.186 --> 05:53.727
<i> It makes it real tricky</i>
<i> to chase that heat.</i>

05:53.771 --> 05:56.521
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:56.565 --> 05:58.190
- Look at the color
of Jo's fire

05:58.233 --> 05:59.941
compared to the color
of Pete's fire,

05:59.985 --> 06:02.819
which is now
just a smoky mass.

06:02.863 --> 06:05.989
- Working with the hand-crank
forge is a challenge.

06:06.033 --> 06:07.741
<i> Never started one</i>
<i> quite like this.</i>

06:07.785 --> 06:09.284
<i> I've started coal forges,</i>

06:09.328 --> 06:11.828
but this is a little
different horse to ride.

06:11.872 --> 06:12.954
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:12.998 --> 06:16.375
I-I struggle with it.

06:16.418 --> 06:19.669
I'm gonna try and make
a kind of a camp chopper.

06:19.713 --> 06:21.088
Get done with it,

06:21.131 --> 06:23.840
it'll whack 2-inch limbs
or thicker,

06:23.884 --> 06:25.717
cut a pig in half,
what have you.

06:25.761 --> 06:26.760
It'll chop.

06:26.804 --> 06:29.179
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:29.223 --> 06:31.056
- I'm real comfortable
in a coal forge.

06:31.100 --> 06:34.351
I've done public demonstrations
on coal forges.

06:34.395 --> 06:36.937
I'm aiming to make
a competition cutter.

06:36.980 --> 06:39.481
Don't need to stab anything.
It doesn't need a point.

06:39.525 --> 06:43.985
I just need to drop this down,
thin it out, set this handle,

06:44.029 --> 06:47.155
give it a nice shape,
make it comfortable.

06:47.199 --> 06:50.492
Everything else, if I can
get this [bleep] going,

06:50.536 --> 06:52.077
should be fine.

06:52.121 --> 06:53.745
Generally when I work
in a coal forge,

06:53.789 --> 06:55.997
there's an electric blower,
so there's always

06:56.041 --> 06:59.918
a steady stream of air
going through that fire.

06:59.962 --> 07:02.129
<i> With a hand-crank blower,</i>

07:02.172 --> 07:04.464
<i> if you're not cranking,</i>
<i> it's not getting air,</i>

07:04.508 --> 07:06.383
and it will die out
if you leave it long enough.

07:06.427 --> 07:08.218
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:08.262 --> 07:11.430
- You have three hours remaining
to finish your work!

07:11.473 --> 07:13.223
- Thank God.
We gonna need it.

07:13.267 --> 07:15.809
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:18.230 --> 07:20.355
[humming circus music]

07:20.399 --> 07:22.607
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:22.651 --> 07:25.152
- Seems like all I can do today
is drop forge.

07:25.195 --> 07:27.070
- Jo's really struggling
with his blade.

07:27.114 --> 07:28.530
It doesn't look like
it's up to temperature.

07:28.574 --> 07:30.490
It was on the floor
just now.

07:30.534 --> 07:31.908
I mean,
his steel doesn't look

07:31.952 --> 07:34.202
like it's
very hot at all.

07:34.246 --> 07:38.665
- Easiest way to get crack is
hit your blade while it's cold.

07:38.709 --> 07:41.126
Working that metal cold,
you're just building problems

07:41.170 --> 07:42.419
into the blade.
- Right.

07:42.463 --> 07:45.338
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:45.382 --> 07:48.049
- Pete's got
some fire issues.

07:48.093 --> 07:49.759
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:49.803 --> 07:53.346
- Just been fighting my fire
for the last hour.

07:53.390 --> 07:59.227
I get it hot, and I lose it,
and, uh, I am, uh, upset.

07:59.271 --> 08:00.937
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:03.108 --> 08:06.401
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:06.445 --> 08:08.153
- Getting the steel
flattened out.

08:08.197 --> 08:10.280
I decide I'm not gonna use
this big chunk of steel.

08:10.324 --> 08:12.032
<i> I'm just gonna use</i>
<i> a small piece of it.</i>

08:12.075 --> 08:14.743
Come on, now.

08:14.786 --> 08:18.121
It has to be
between 10 and 12 inches long.

08:18.165 --> 08:20.290
All right, so I'm thinking
I want to forge out

08:20.334 --> 08:23.502
<i> as much of this</i>
<i> as I possibly can.</i>

08:23.545 --> 08:24.920
Heat, beat, repeat.

08:24.963 --> 08:30.342
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:30.385 --> 08:33.762
- You have only two hours
remaining to finish your work!

08:33.805 --> 08:36.181
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:36.225 --> 08:37.933
- Hot as balls.

08:37.976 --> 08:40.310
- It is intense,
isn't it?

08:40.354 --> 08:43.438
- Never, ever enough time.

08:43.482 --> 08:46.066
I'm most concerned with getting
some of this thickness out.

08:46.109 --> 08:47.734
<i> I need to gain</i>
<i> a little bit of length,</i>

08:47.778 --> 08:51.988
<i> and I need to get rid</i>
<i> of some meat on this.</i>

08:52.032 --> 08:55.784
- April's having a hard time.
We're seeing fatigue.

08:55.827 --> 08:57.536
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:57.579 --> 08:59.829
It's the comfort level
that's dropping.

08:59.873 --> 09:01.581
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:01.625 --> 09:04.209
<i> - I do do a fair amount</i>
<i> of coal forge work,</i>

09:04.253 --> 09:06.586
but this is your hammer arm,
and you're cranking,

09:06.630 --> 09:08.547
and you're cranking,
and you're hammering.

09:08.590 --> 09:12.300
<i> And your arm gets tired</i>
<i> really quickly.</i>

09:12.344 --> 09:15.387
I got a warp in here
that I got to get out.

09:15.430 --> 09:19.140
At home, I would have
a power hammer,

09:19.184 --> 09:25.105
which moves things a lot faster
than little old me.

09:25.148 --> 09:28.483
Now, it's all about me
and the hammer.

09:28.527 --> 09:31.987
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:32.030 --> 09:34.197
- I'm not getting air flow
like I should.

09:34.241 --> 09:37.951
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:37.995 --> 09:39.786
Sorry, Brandon.

09:39.830 --> 09:42.372
- Good strategy on his part
against Brandon.

09:42.416 --> 09:44.749
If he can
smoke Brandon out,

09:44.793 --> 09:48.753
then he doesn't have to worry
about him in the first round.

09:48.797 --> 09:52.257
Pete needs to dump his ash
and then his fire will work.

09:52.301 --> 09:54.884
He hasn't gone and did
the simplest things,

09:54.928 --> 09:56.428
the parts of that equipment

09:56.471 --> 09:59.139
that are made to open
that air channel up.

09:59.182 --> 10:00.599
They're there.

10:00.642 --> 10:02.100
- I realized in the bottom
of the forge

10:02.144 --> 10:04.227
is a place
to catch ash.

10:04.271 --> 10:07.105
If that gets plugged up,
you're not going to have heat.

10:07.149 --> 10:08.523
- There he goes,
there he goes.

10:08.567 --> 10:11.192
[all cheering]
- Yay, Pete! Yay!

10:11.236 --> 10:12.944
- There it is.

10:12.988 --> 10:16.239
- I get a lot of stuff
that falls out of my forge,

10:16.283 --> 10:17.866
and all of a sudden
I got heat again,

10:17.909 --> 10:20.660
and I'm breathing
a sigh of relief.

10:20.704 --> 10:23.622
Ohh, I can
get on with this now.

10:23.665 --> 10:27.083
- You have just one hour
remaining to finish your work!

10:27.127 --> 10:29.044
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:29.087 --> 10:31.171
- Does this dirt make me
look fat?

10:31.214 --> 10:37.677
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:37.721 --> 10:39.304
- Damn.

10:39.348 --> 10:42.557
- Brandon came out of the gate
like a thoroughbred,

10:42.601 --> 10:46.519
and now he's slowing down
to about a burro's pace.

10:46.563 --> 10:48.813
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:48.857 --> 10:50.815
<i> - At this point, my arm's</i>
<i> already cramping and hurting.</i>

10:50.859 --> 10:53.068
I said, "You know what?
If you can't do this, Brandon,

10:53.111 --> 10:53.985
there's no point, man."

10:54.029 --> 10:55.570
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

10:55.614 --> 10:57.530
- His fire,
it looks like it's low.

10:57.574 --> 10:59.407
He's not moving
very fast.

10:59.451 --> 11:01.826
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:01.870 --> 11:03.703
I'm just not sure
where he's at physically

11:03.747 --> 11:05.580
and mentally
at this point.

11:05.624 --> 11:07.290
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:07.334 --> 11:09.376
- I'm thinking to myself,
"Man, Brandon,

11:09.419 --> 11:10.835
"you're stepping off
into a world of [bleep]

11:10.879 --> 11:15.340
that you can't handle,"
and at this point,

11:15.384 --> 11:19.052
I'm thinking I'm just
gonna lay my tools down...

11:19.096 --> 11:20.387
that I can't handle this.

11:20.430 --> 11:23.139
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:30.190 --> 11:32.649
- I'm really worried
about Brandon.

11:32.693 --> 11:35.318
- He doesn't have
good body language.

11:35.362 --> 11:37.237
- I'm really starting
to doubt myself,

11:37.280 --> 11:40.198
<i> and at this point,</i>

11:40.242 --> 11:43.743
I'm thinking I'm just gonna
lay my tools down,

11:43.787 --> 11:46.621
that I can't handle this,
you know?

11:46.665 --> 11:49.499
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:49.543 --> 11:53.086
But then I think
of my daughter.

11:53.130 --> 11:56.214
[clears throat]

11:56.258 --> 12:00.719
And-and in that moment,
everything turned around.

12:00.762 --> 12:02.429
It's like Thor himself
came down

12:02.472 --> 12:03.847
and punched me
square in the chest

12:03.890 --> 12:05.849
and said,
"No, Brandon,

12:05.892 --> 12:08.143
<i> "you're gonna do this.</i>
<i> You're gonna make it, man.</i>

12:08.186 --> 12:10.520
You're gonna show everybody
that you can do this."

12:14.109 --> 12:15.817
Victory or Valhalla.

12:15.861 --> 12:19.446
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:19.489 --> 12:21.948
- I have made
way prettier things,

12:21.992 --> 12:26.077
but this one is...
what it is.

12:26.121 --> 12:31.416
- April's edge is really turning
that nice color of orange.

12:31.460 --> 12:34.794
There she goes,
in the quench.

12:34.838 --> 12:36.671
